## ITERATION 42 BODY

title: "042 — Vehicle Marker Anchor + Directional Arrow Contrast"
description: "Correct route anchoring to the vehicle center and improve directional arrow readability with a sharp outline-style shadow."

:::GOALS

Ensure vehicle routes originate from the true center of the vehicle marker.

Improve directional arrow visibility so it reads clearly against satellite terrain.

Preserve the marker hierarchy where the arrow appears visually above the route line.

:::END

:::TASKS

Route anchoring

Ensure route polylines originate from the center of the vehicle marker rather than the edge of the operational ring.

Adjust the route start coordinate or rendering logic so the first route segment aligns with the marker center point.

Verify the route visually connects to the vehicle center regardless of marker size.

Z-order correction

Ensure the directional arrow renders visually above the route line.

Adjust layering or z-index so the arrow is never visually obscured by route segments.

Directional arrow contrast

Improve arrow readability by replacing the current soft shadow with a sharp-edged outline effect.

Implement a crisp, non-blurred shadow that behaves like a thin outline around the arrow.

The outline should:

- increase contrast against the map terrain
- remain subtle
- avoid glow or blur effects

Marker layering

Maintain the existing marker hierarchy:

1. outer operational ring
2. center marker body
3. directional arrow

The directional arrow must visually sit above the route and remain the clearest orientation signal.

:::END

:::ACCEPTANCE

- Route lines originate from the center of the vehicle marker.
- The route does not visually attach to the outer ring.
- The directional arrow always renders above the route line.
- The arrow uses a crisp outline-style shadow instead of a blurred shadow.
- Arrow orientation remains easy to read against satellite imagery.

:::END